Bubblemaps v1.0

Giuseppe Dâ€™Agostino


This is a base graphics implementation of a bubblechart arranged as a heatmap, i.e.Â with rows and columns arranged by hiearchical clustering. It is currently used to map numerical values (such as correlation) to colours, and a second set of numerical values (assumed to be p-values, thus log-transformed and filtered for significance) to dot size. 

require(viridis)
require(pheatmap)


Letâ€™s simulate a correlation matrix by taking values from a random uniform distribution between -0.8 and 0.8.

cors = data.frame(matrix(runif(n = 100, min = -0.8, max = 0.8), nrow = 10, ncol = 10))


We now simulate associated p-values. To do this we will first simulate a uniform distribution, then â€œspike inâ€ some low p-values for high absolute correlations ( > 0.55). 

pvals = matrix(runif(n = 100, min = 0, max = 1), nrow = 10, ncol = 10)
pvals[which(abs(cors) > 0.55)] = runif(n = length(which(abs(cors) > 0.55)), min = 1e-05, max = 1e-03)
pvals = as.data.frame(pvals, stringsAsFactors = F)


Letâ€™s look at the p value distribution to make sure it looks like a nice enough result, worth plotting 

hist(as.matrix(pvals), breaks = 10, col = "cadetblue", border = NA)


We first define a function that draws a blank canvas with the size we need. It is a grid of x by y that will be populated by another function 

makeGrid = function(ys, xs, ...)
{
    plot(y = 1:ys, x = rep(1, ys), xlim = c(1,xs), ...)
    for(i in 2:xs) points(y = 1:ys, x = rep(i,ys), ...)
}

We then define another function that maps dot sizes to values (cex). This function takes as arguments the values, bins (number of different dot sizes), a minimum (minc) and a maximum (maxc) dot size, a value with which NA values are replaced (na.value) and a value with which infinite values are replaced (inf.value)

prop_cex <- function(values, bins, minc = 0.3, maxc = 3, na.value = 0, inf.value = 400)
{   
    values[is.na(values)] = na.value
    values[!is.finite(values)] = inf.value
    
    ordered.values <- values[order(values, decreasing = T)]

    cex.values <- seq(minc, maxc, length.out = length(unique(values)))
    cex.frame <- as.data.frame(cbind(cex.values, lfc =rev(unique(ordered.values))))
    cex.binned <- seq(minc, maxc, length.out = bins)
    outdf <- as.data.frame(values)
    outdf$cex.values = sapply(outdf$values, function (x) cex.frame[which(cex.frame$lfc == x),1])
    cex.values.binned = as.data.frame(sapply(outdf$cex.values, function(x) cut(x, breaks = cex.binned, include.lowest = T, labels = cex.binned[1:length(cex.binned)-1] )), stringsAsFactors = F)
    outdf$binned = as.numeric(levels(cex.values.binned[,1])[cex.values.binned[,1]])
    return(outdf$binned)
}

The third function we need to define maps colors to values, and is directly taken by the pheatmap package. It takes as arguments the values and the color palette of choice.

colorKey <- function(values, pal = viridis(25, option = "B"))
{
    require(pheatmap)
    values_sc <- scale(values)
    bks <- pheatmap:::generate_breaks(values_sc, length(pal), center = F)
    cols <- pheatmap:::scale_colours(values_sc, col=pal, breaks=bks, na_col = "gray")
    cols <- as.character(cols)
    return(cols)
}

Finally, we define the actual bubblemap function. Having defined all the other parts separately, it is trivial to plot the dots with their respective colors and sizes in the grid. This function takes as arguments the data frame of values, the data frame of p values, the number of dot size bins (passed to prop_cex), the color palette (passed to colorKey), the map title (maplabel passed in â€œmainâ€ to the plot function). sp is a spacer used to draw the color key properly.

bubbleMap <- function(valuedf, pvaluedf, cbins = 5, sp = 1, color_pal = colorRampPalette(c("slateblue", "gray", "orange"))(25), maplabel = 
    "Correlation")
{
    pmap <- pheatmap(valuedf, silent = T)
    valuedf <- valuedf[rev(pmap$tree_row$order), pmap$tree_col$order]
    pvaluedf <- pvaluedf[rev(pmap$tree_row$order), pmap$tree_col$order]
    logP = as.numeric(-log10(unlist(pvaluedf)))
    logP[logP < 1.3] = 1
    cexes = prop_cex(logP, bins = cbins, minc = 1, maxc = 4.4)
    cexes[logP == 1] = 0.5
    pcex = as.data.frame(cbind(10^-logP, cexes))
    pcex = pcex[order(pcex[,1]),]
    edgen = round(max(c(abs(min(as.numeric(unlist(valuedf)))), abs(max(as.numeric(unlist(valuedf)))))), digits = 1)
    colors = colorKey(values = c(- edgen, edgen, as.numeric(unlist(valuedf))), pal = color_pal)
    colors = colors[3:length(colors)]
    nr = nrow(valuedf)
    nc = ncol(valuedf)
    par(mar= c(5,5,5,5))
    makeGrid(nr + (nr/(3+sp)), nc, cex = 0, ylab = NA, xlab = NA, yaxt = 'n', xaxt = 'n', ylim = c(0,nr + (nr/(3+sp))), bty = 'n')
    abline(h = 1:nr, col = 'gray')
    for(i in 1:nc) points(y = 1:nr, x = rep(i,nr), cex = cexes[((nr*i)-(nr-1)):(nr*i)], col = colors[((nr*i)-(nr-1)):(nr*i)], pch = 16)
    axis(1, at = 1:nc, labels = colnames(valuedf) , las = 2, cex.axis=0.9)
    axis(4, at = 1:nr, labels = rownames(valuedf), las = 2, cex.axis = 0.7)
    rect_series = seq(1, nc/2, length.out = length(color_pal) + 1)
    for(q in 1:length(color_pal)) 
        {
            rect(rect_series[q], nr + (nr/(8+sp)), rect_series[q+1], nr + (nr/(9+sp)), col = color_pal[q], border = NA)
        } 
    rect(1, nr + (nr/(8+sp)), nc/2, nr + (nr/(9+sp)))
    text(x = 1, y = nr + (nr/(7+sp/2)), labels = paste("-", edgen))
    text(x = nc/2, y = nr + (nr/(7+sp/2)), labels = edgen)
    text(x = 1+(((nc/2)-1)/2), y = nr + (nr/(7+sp/2)), labels = maplabel)
    cvec = vector()
    for(i in 1:length(unique(pcex$cexes)))
    {
        cvec[i] <- pcex[which(pcex$cexes == unique(pcex$cexes)[i])[length(which(pcex$cexes == unique(pcex$cexes)[i]))],1]   
    }
    cvec = cvec[1:(length(cvec)-1)]
    cxvec = c("p > 0.05", paste("p <=", rev(formatC(cvec, format = "e", digits = 2))))
    points(x = seq(nc-(nc/15), nc-(nc/2) + ((nc/2)/2), length.out = length(unique(cexes))), cex = unique(cexes)[order(unique(cexes), decreasing = T)], y = rep(nr + (nr/(9+sp)), length(unique(cexes))), col = 'gray', pch = 16)
    text(x = seq(nc-(nc/15), nc-(nc/2) + ((nc/2)/2), length.out = length(cxvec)), y = rep(nr + (nr/(7.5+sp)), length(unique(cexes))), labels = rev(cxvec), cex = 0.7, srt = 45, pos = 4)

}

Letâ€™s now apply the function to our simulated correlations and p values:

bubbleMap(cors, pvals, color_pal = viridis(25, option = "D"))
